 on Medicaid for their care, were told the state would not fund any more treatment — but would pay for their assisted suicide.“Don’t think that couldn’t happen here.”And one multiple sclerosis (MS) sufferer said she was incensed by the report.FearedKathryn Higham feared she was going to die when she was diagnosed with MS in 1999.“I was so relieved when I found out it was not a terminal condition, I realised my life was precious,” she said.“You shouldn’t be ending your life, every breath is precious.”Weekly video newsShare this pageFollow usFacebookYouTubeTwitterHeadline WidgetNews feedsMailing listRelated articles‘Biased’ assisted suicide report under fire from criticsDon’t weaken euthanasia law based on rare cases, says doctorParalysed footballer lands talent scout jobDr Death group boasts of helping five Scots’ suicidesDutch doctors end the life of senile dementia patientTop news nowBoots faces criticism over sale of sex toysNo safe way to allow assisted suicide, admits Lord FalconerGay editor: ‘we will teach your kids the new norms’Christian radio station will be allowed to challenge ad banBritain’s oldest married couple celebrate 75 yearsArticle categoriesMedical ethicsRecent news | Publications | MPs' votes | Apologetics | Contact | Support usCopyright © The Christian Institute All Rights ReservedRegistered office: The Christian Institute, Wilberforce House, 4 Park Road, Gosforth Business Park, Newcastle upon Tyne, NE12 8DG
